To comply with EU targets and the resulting increase in power demand, Europe could see its installed wind and solar base quadruple. https://t.co/GlDLgeQaOv

The growing need to electrify more, from passenger cars and heat pumps, to electrolyzers and industrial motors, means electricity could account for roughly half of primary energy consumption by 2030, versus about 20% today.

Europe is on the cusp of an electrification push that could lead to a roughly 50% increase in power demand through 2030. üìà For example, when a typical European household acquires an electric vehicle and installs a heat pump, its electricity consumption rises three-fold. https://t.co/09r8mb5OlX

Our economists now expect the Fed to raise rates by 25 bps at each of their remaining policy meetings this year. They forecast the central bank will start reducing its balance sheet in June.

Higher oil and gas prices will help drive the shift to green energy. üåé 

As the cost of capital goes up and hydrocarbons become more expensive, low-carbon alternatives become relatively cheaper. https://t.co/3zBuEkk9Re

The restraint on oil and gas investing has broken the link between rising energy prices and increased investment. 

As carbon-heavy companies use less of their cash for new capacity, it makes share buybacks, dividends and M&A more likely.
Meanwhile a lack of global policy coordination is causing uncertainty among corporate executives, resulting in less re-investment. https://t.co/grk4uXjRqb

As investors focus on climate change, the cost of capital is now 15 percentage points higher for high-carbon energy projects than it is for low-carbon ones, says Michele Della Vigna, our Head of Natural Resources Research in EMEA. https://t.co/oEuwj0XAwK

Oil prices are soaring üìà, but investment into fossil fuels has stalled. 

Find out what that means for energy prices and the transition to green energy. üëá https://t.co/2I5ZPldeep

But if inflation stays high enough, the Fed could end up hiking more than five times, raising rates at every meeting later this year. 

Learn more: https://t.co/miAq7VX5Kp

To be sure, it‚Äôs not guaranteed that the Fed will hike five times. 

We could see fewer hikes if the economy slows dramatically, financial conditions tighten too much, or the pandemic fades and inflation recedes.
Chair Jerome Powell recently made it clear that Fed leadership is open to tightening more aggressively, saying policymakers will move ‚Äústeadily‚Äù away from the current stance.

Their read on the latest wage data is that the pace of wage growth is ‚Äútoo hot‚Äù for the Fed‚Äôs 2% inflation goal.

A key data point: Private industry wages and salaries (excluding incentive paid occupations) rose at a 5.7% quarterly annualized pace in Q4.
GS Research economists think the Fed will raise its benchmark interest rate five times this year üìà‚Äîup from their earlier forecast of four hikes in 2022. Here‚Äôs why. üëá

Text: For more, see our interview with Mericle and Phillips in the latest BRIEFINGS from Goldman Sachs and subscribe here: https://t.co/eVciDU17a1

And finally on inflation: It‚Äôs ‚Äúlikely to get worse before it gets better,‚Äù Mericle says. 

‚ÄúBut by the end of the year we expect core PCE inflation to fall below 3%, though CPI is likely to remain quite a bit higher.‚Äù

On employment, Mericle expects continued strength after significant improvement last year. 

‚ÄúWith labor demand still red hot and enhanced unemployment benefits now expired, we expect the unemployment rate to fall to a 50-year low of 3.4% by the end of 2022.‚Äù

That is in part because of diminished expectations for fiscal stimulus. 

While political economist Alec Phillips expects Congress to raise spending this year, the impact is likely to be modest and spread over years. https://t.co/UXU9N6kWl6
While consensus expects GDP growth of 3.4% in 2022 on a Q4/Q4 basis, Goldman Sachs expects 2.4%, U.S. chief economist David Mericle says.
